^B@2^*Bhondo717:^*N|cp||at| Well played. Let us discuss the short club treatment that cp plays. Some people play that if you open 1@D you have to have at least a 4 card suit. Therefore, very occasionally, with precisely 4-4-3-2 distribution, you are forced to open 1@C with a doubleton club. My personal preference is to just play better minor, because sometimes you are forced to open 1@C with 3-3 in the minors when you have much better diamonds.|
PG| ***** 18 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|But certainly short club is reasonable if you like it better. However, responder still needs to pass with less than six points, even if they are short in clubs. Some people play that responder must bid, even with zero points if he/she does not have clubs, but that is really not playable. As to the question about mini-roman, some people play that a 2@D opener shows a 3 suited hand (4-4-4-1 or 5-4-4) with 11-15 HCP. |
PG| ***** 19 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at| If you play that, then cp's hand qualifies as a 2@D opener. But as all of you know, I love weak 2s :), so I would never play mini-roman. However, some people do play it. My feeling about mini-roman is you can show the hand other ways, and weak 2 diamonds comes up a lot more.

Also, some people play Flannery 2@D, which shows 5 hearts, 4 spades, and 11-15. I usually am not this opinionated, but I think Flannery is one of the silliest conventions ever invented, lol. I really recommend against playing it.|
