NT||cp|8|fp|2|AT|^B@2^Y@3^*BHoward: ^*N|cp||fp||at|OK, let me discuss the play first. cp defended very nicely. After trick one, cp knows that her partner only started with one club. The Q is the only outstanding club, and if partner had it, she would have led it. And it was smart to retain the ace of clubs and not set up a club trick for dee. Had dee played the @CQ, cp would assume partner started with @C108. Next, dee made a slight error towards the end. After she ruffs the club with the J of spades, there are only 3 spades left. She should play the K to draw 2 of them, hoping they are 2-1, and then play diamonds and hearts. That way, they only score one trump trick, instead of the 2 they scored.|
PG| ***** 41 ***** |


NT||cp|8|fp|2|AT|^B@2^Y@3^*BHoward: ^*N|cp||fp||at|As, to the bidding everything through the negative double is fine. cp could bid 1N, to show her spade card. Normally I would like to have another spade, but 1N is reasonable. However, another bid you could make is 2@C, since you have a good 5 card suit. A rebid of 2@C does not show six, particularly in that sequence. You often rebid a 5 card minor. Suppose you have a hand that is 1-4-3-5 for example, and the auction goes 1@C-1@S.
You could rebid 1N, but that is really a lie. 2@C is better.|
PG| ***** 42 ***** |


NT||cp|8|fp|2|AT|^B@2^Y@3^*BHoward: ^*N|cp||fp||at|In a major suit, a rebid at the 2 level tends to show six. But if you open 1 of a minor, you often rebid a 5 card suit. That is why I said 1N was ok, but so is 2@C. Now, let us discuss isabable's options. Even over 1N, isabable could consider bidding 2@H. because she made a negative double. 2@H shows 5+ good hearts and less than enough points to bid 2@H over 1@S (so less than 10 or so).|
